definitions.definition: A color reminiscent of pinks, the flowers. [from 17th c.]
examples: My new dress is a wonderful shade of pink .

subdefinitions.definition: Magenta , the colour evoked by red and blue light when combined.

definitions.definition: Any of various flowers of that colour in the genus Dianthus , sometimes called carnations . [from 16th c.]
examples: This garden in particular has a beautiful bed of pinks .

definitions.definition: ( dated ) A perfect example; excellence , perfection ; the embodiment of some quality. [from 16th c.]
examples: Your hat, madam, is the very pink of fashion.

definitions.definition: Hunting pink ; scarlet , as worn by hunters. [from 18th c.]
( snooker ) One of the colour balls used in snooker , coloured pink, with a value of 6 points. [from 19th c.]
examples: Oh dear, he's left himself snookered behind the pink .

definitions.definition: ( slang ) An unlettered and uncultured, but relatively prosperous, member of the middle classes; compare Babbitt , bourgeoisie .

definitions.definition: ( obsolete ) A small hole made by puncturing something, as with a rapier, dagger, or pinking iron .

subdefinitions.definition: ( obsolete ) A small hole or puncture made by a sharp, slender instrument such as a rapier, poniard or dagger, or (by extension) a bullet ; a stab .
( obsolete ) A small hole or eyelet punched in a garment for decoration, as with a pinking iron ; a scallop.

definitions.definition: Any of various lake pigments or dyes in yellow , yellowish green or brown shades, made with plant coloring and a metallic oxide base.
